{
  "query": "What are the documented effects of adding soil amendments like charcoal, sulphur, or carbon before or after seeding on grassland vegetation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available studies, soil amendments of charcoal, sulphur, and carbon have varying effects on grassland vegetation depending on the amendment type and timing.\n\nCarbon amendments: Two studies in the USA found that adding carbon to soil after sowing seeds either reduced or did not alter the density of sown forb species (Action 3433).\n\nCharcoal amendments: One study in the Netherlands found that adding charcoal to soil before sowing seeds did not alter overall plant biomass or grass cover, but increased the cover of legumes while not altering the cover of other forbs (Action 3422).\n\nSulphur amendments: Studies in the UK and USA showed mixed effects. Adding sulphur to soil before seeding reduced plant species richness in one study but showed no change in another study. Adding sulphur before sowing reduced overall vegetation cover but increased the cover of three of six sown species when applied in low amounts. Native plant species cover and richness were not altered by sulphur addition (Action 3428). When sulphur was added alongside sowing, it did not increase heather cover in most cases and had mixed effects on various grass species. However, adding sulphur alongside planting heather seedlings increased their survival, though survival remained very low after two years (Action 1710).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3433",
    "3422",
    "3428",
    "1710"
  ]
}

