{
  "query": "In European grasslands, how does post-seeding management by mowing compare to livestock grazing for enhancing sown species?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on European studies, post-seeding management by mowing and livestock grazing show different effects on enhancing sown species. Mowing after seeding/planting has been found to increase plant species richness compared to grazing with livestock in one UK study (Action 3419). Additionally, mowing after sowing seeds increased the richness of sown species in another UK study, and cutting sown plots each year with removal of cut vegetation increased sown grass and forb species richness compared to cutting without removing vegetation (Action 3419). Mowing after sowing also increased the abundance of sown forb species in one UK study and increased the abundance of five of seven sown forb species when mowing was more frequent in a German study (Action 3419). In contrast, livestock grazing after seeding showed mixed results for sown species enhancement. One UK study found that grazing with cattle after sowing seeds increased sown species richness compared to grazing with sheep, but another UK study found that grazing with cattle reduced the cover of sown species compared to grazing with sheep (Action 3423). However, one Italian study found that grazing with livestock after sowing seeds increased plant species richness compared to sowing without grazing (Action 3423). The evidence suggests that annual mowing after sowing can increase plant community similarity to natural grassland and that cutting vegetation three times per year after sowing increased the richness of characteristic grassland species compared to cutting once per year (Action 3419).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3419",
    "3423"
  ]
}

