{"query": "What does the evidence from different continents suggest about how sowing different seed types—such as just grasses versus mixed grass and forbs—affects forb abundance?", "summary": "Evidence from studies across multiple continents shows contrasting effects of different seeding strategies on forb abundance. Studies of sowing native grass and forbs together found that this approach increased forb species richness in 71% of cases in the UK (action 3432). Three of four replicated, randomized, controlled studies in the Czech Republic and the USA found that sowing native grass and forb seeds increased the cover or density of forb species, though one study found that forb cover increased after one year but did not differ from unsown areas after 10 years (action 3432). The studies examining sowing native grass and forbs were conducted across Europe (36 studies), North America (12 studies), and New Zealand (1 study), with one review including studies from Europe, North America and Africa (action 3432).

In contrast, evidence from sowing grass seeds only shows different results for forb abundance. One of two replicated studies in the USA and Canada found that sowing grass seeds reduced the abundance of native forb species, while the other study found no change in the density of native forb species (action 3397). These grass-only seeding studies were conducted across North America (6 studies), Europe (5 studies), Canada (1 study), and South Africa (1 study) (action 3397).

When examining seeding density effects, one replicated, randomized, paired, controlled study in the USA found that sowing seeds at a higher density increased both forb species richness and forb cover (action 3405).", "action_ids": ["3432","3397","3405"]}

